  "updated_summary": "In a dimly lit office, a cartoon Animated Scientist sits opposite an Older Man in Office, who is seated behind a wooden desk with a serious expression, as a narrator explains the financial gamble taken by 'Ogawa' on 'Nakamura's moonshot project,' dedicating '500 million yen or 3 million dollars,' approximately '15% of the company's annual profit,' with on-screen text displaying '¥500,000,000' and '1.5%'. The scene shifts to a live-action shot of a bearded Man in a dark room who turns on a vintage-style Incandescent Light Bulb, illuminating his face and revealing its filament, while on-screen text highlights its inefficiency: '94-98% heat' and '2-6% light'. The Man explains that incandescent bulbs, a symbol for ideas, are 'terrible at making light' by heating a tungsten filament until it glows, emitting most radiation as infrared heat and only a small fraction as visible light. He then presents a glowing Red LED in his other hand, with on-screen text 'light-emitting diode' and '50-70% light', emphasizing that LEDs 'primarily create light, so they're far more efficient'."
